div.h1: General Principles for data transformations (in no specific order)

div.style: font-size: 20px

ol.li: Practice immutability. Each row should only be written once to a table. In other words, do not insert a row and then update it in a subsequent step.Â
As much as possible, break a complex transformation into various sub-steps. Adopt single responsibility.
Join datasets from different data sources as late as possible. Decoupling helps manage changes better.
Facts/Events should always have a business timestamp and an arrival timestamp.
Perform upserts by primary keys only. Never delete-insert based on timestamps alone.
Avoid upserts if you care about bitemporal history.Â
Cleaning data is an anti-pattern. Avoid cleaning data. If you must, do this in a separate step in the transformation flow.
Do not model anything motivated purely by ease-of-use or convenience. Each transformation step must be "valuable".
Avoid querying source tables that are more than 2 layers below the target layer.
Never re-implement any business logic from source systems.Â
Use unmaterialized views where possible for Aggregations (Views in Snowflake and BQ are cheap to build and change, but have some limitations
Do not create / invent any fundamentally new domain entity directly in the data warehouse. If you must, do this deliberately and not as a side-effect of some other transformation.
Do not coalesce multiple attributes into a single attribute. Coalesces are hard to reason about. Instead, use records/structs to store multiple values.
Do not model anything in a visualization layer like Tableau/Looker. Those models are hard to reason about and can not be reused outside the tool.
Create multiple usage-centric views/aggregations of the same data instead of creating a Frankenstein's dataset.Â
Tables should evolve using principles of API evolution. Create a new version, communicate to users, migrate and deprecate.
